T1  - Organizational Cosmopolitanism and Innovativeness
AU  - Robertson, Thomas S.
AU  - Wind, Yoram
Y1  - 1983/06/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255980
DO  - 10.5465/255980
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 332
EP  - 338
VL  - 26
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses a research on organizational cosmopolitanism and innovativeness. Individual cosmopolitanism scores were correlated against the number of innovations adopted by the organization. The cosmopolitanism-innovativeness relationship was also examined on a multiperson organizational basis. The highest innovativeness was seen in hospitals characterized by a cosmopolitan professional and a local administrator, whereas the lowest innovativeness was seen in hospitals with a local professional and a local administrator. The authors believe the use of typology of organizational cosmopolitanism seems to have value in research on organizational innovativeness.
AB  - The article discusses a research on organizational cosmopolitanism and innovativeness. Individual cosmopolitanism scores were correlated against the number of innovations adopted by the organization. The cosmopolitanism-innovativeness relationship was also examined on a multiperson organizational basis. The highest innovativeness was seen in hospitals characterized by a cosmopolitan professional and a local administrator, whereas the lowest innovativeness was seen in hospitals with a local professional and a local administrator. The authors believe the use of typology of organizational cosmopolitanism seems to have value in research on organizational innovativeness.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255980
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255980
Y2  - 2026/04/24
