TY  - JOUR
T1  - Sex Differences in Job Satisfaction Revisited
AU  - Varca, Philip E.
AU  - Shaffer, Garnett Stokes
AU  - McCauley, Cynthia D.
Y1  - 1983/06/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255982
DO  - 10.5465/255982
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 348
EP  - 353
VL  - 26
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses a research on sex differences in job satisfaction. Subjects of the study included 200 males and 192 females who received questionnaire at their home and reported full time employment at the same job for at least one year. Findings indicated that sex differences in job satisfaction revolve around organizational rewards and that such differences are moderated by occupational level. Results showed that upper level men and lower level women are more satisfied with their pay and promotions.
AB  - The article discusses a research on sex differences in job satisfaction. Subjects of the study included 200 males and 192 females who received questionnaire at their home and reported full time employment at the same job for at least one year. Findings indicated that sex differences in job satisfaction revolve around organizational rewards and that such differences are moderated by occupational level. Results showed that upper level men and lower level women are more satisfied with their pay and promotions.
SN  - 0001-4273
